    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-31T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-31T22:00:00-05:00" n="891"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d891">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.2361A/8–144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Vladivostok</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ward</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vladivostok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-01T13:00:00+10:00"
                            >August 1, 1944—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>34. Diplomatic agent<note n="91" xml:id="d891fn1">Semen Petrovich Dyukarev,
                        representative in Vladivostok of the Soviet People’s Commissariat for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> has just informed me that on July 29 at 18 hours 34
                    minutes 150 East Meridian time, an American airplane B–29, number 32, landed on
                    an airdrome in the vicinity of Ugolna, about 30 kilometers to the north of
                    Vladivostok.</p>
                <p>The crew, which consists of 11 persons, is in good health.</p>
                <p>Before landing the crew destroyed all documents, radio equipment and bomb
                    sight.</p>
                <p>Pursuant to international law, the crew has been interned.</p>
                <pb facs="0993" n="983" xml:id="pg_983"/>
                <p>He is of the opinion that this airplane took part in the bombing of Mukden and he
                    has reason to believe that the cause of the landing was shortage of fuel.</p>
                <p>Commanding officer of the airplane has requested access to me and tentative
                    arrangements have been made for my travel to Ugolna tomorrow afternoon.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ward</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
